
Breast cancer staging isn’t just about tumor size anymore. Doctors now factor in biology, like hormone receptors, HER2, and tumor grade, to see how aggressive the cancer really is. This means it is a possiblity that two patients with tumors of the same size may end up with very different stages. For radiologists, it’s about connecting what they see on scans with lab results and molecular data. The goal is to give each patient care that fits their specific situation and outlook.
    Koh, J., & Kim, M. J. (2019). Introduction of a New Staging System of Breast Cancer for Radiologists: An Emphasis on the Prognostic Stage. Korean journal of radiology, 20(1), 69–82. https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2018.0231 Links to an external site.

The study looked at almost 200,000 women in the U.S. and compared breast cancer survival by molecular subtype. It found that hormone receptor–positive/HER2–negative cancers had the best outcomes, while triple‑negative cancers had the worst. HER2‑positive patients did better than expected in advanced stages because of new targeted therapies. Stage at diagnosis was the biggest factor overall, however race, insurance, and income also did influenced survival. The main point is that biology, treatment advances, and social disparities all shape how patients do. 
    Nadia Howlader, Kathleen A. Cronin, Allison W. Kurian, Rebecca Andridge; Differences in Breast Cancer Survival by Molecular Subtypes in the United States. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev 1 June 2018; 27 (6): 619–626. https://doi.org/10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-17-0627 Links to an external site.

This article is basically a crash course in survival analysis. This is the part of statistics that deals with “time-to-event” data like how long patients live after treatment. It starts by explaining why ordinary averages don’t work when some patients are still alive or lost to follow-up, introducing the idea of censored data. Survival analysis is all about studying how long it takes for something to happen, like how long patients live after treatment. The article explains that regular averages don’t cut it because some patients are still alive or drop out of the study, so researchers need special tools to handle “censored” data. In the end, the article makes clear that survival analysis is a crucial part of medical research because it turns patient timelines into evidence about which treatments actually work.
